Introduction

A new preventative vaccine (covid91) is under test in clinical trials. Given the nature of this vaccine it is suspected that the drug may exhibit different effectiveness across the variety of sub-populations tracked. Consider population subgroups by gender( guys and gals), drug use, and sexual orientation. Write a complete report that separately considers this drug for each subgroup and your recommendations as to whether people in the subgroup should take the vaccine.

\(H_0\) The Null Hypothesis is that among the target population in each following data, the vaccine has no effect on whether one contracts the virus or not.

\(H_A\) The Alternative Hypothesis is that among the target population in each of the following sets of data, the vaccine does have an effect on whether one contracts the virus or not.

Methods

Every question is of a Cat~Cat type.

Results

###Plot barplots

DataF=filter(FinalData,sex=="gal")
barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataF)

barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataF, type="percent", main="gals")

In the frequency bar chart above, titled gals, it appears that the females who had COVID those who took the drug were less effected with the virus, than those females who did not take the drug. Those who did not have COVID appear to not be effected whether they took the drugh or didnt take the drug.

As we observe the percentage bar chart above, titled gals, it appears that similar to the frequency chart, that those females who had the virus, the females who took the drug were less effected than those who didnt take the drug and those females who didnt have the drug.

DataM=filter(FinalData,sex=="guy")
barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataM)

barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataM, type="percent", main="guys")

In the above frequency bar chart, for guys, it appears that the males who had COVID and took the drug were effected more than those males who did not take the drug. We also observe that those males who did not have the virus who did or did not take the drug were equally almost equally non-effected.

Likewise when we observe the bar chart by percentage above for guys, it appears that those males who had the virus and took the drug were more effected with the Virus than those who didnt take the drug, and those who didnt have the virus, were almost equally non-effected whether they took the drug or not.

DataH=filter(FinalData,LGBTQ=="straight")
barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataH)

barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataH, type="percent", main="straight")

In the frequency bar chart above it appears that those who were straight and had COVID, and took the drug were less effected than those who didnt take the drug. Those who did not have the virus, it appears that there wasnt a significant effect on whether or not they took the drug or not.

Similarly, when we observe the bar chart in percentages, those who were straight and had the virus and took the drug were less likely to get the virus than those who did take the drug. Those who didnt have the virus, whether they took the drug or not, did not show a significant effect either way.

DataH=filter(FinalData,LGBTQ=="gay")
barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataH)

barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataH, type="percent", main="gay")

In the above frequency bar chart, we observe that those who were gay and got the virus, were more likely to be effected when taking the drug than those who didnt take the drug. Those who didnt contract the virus and were gay, appear to have no significant effect whether taking the drug or not.

Similarly, in the percentage bar chart, those who were gay and took the drug were significantly more effected with the virus when taking the drug than those who didnt take the drug, and those who were not effected showed no significant difference whether taking the drug or not.

DataU=filter(FinalData,DrugUser=="yes")
barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataU)

barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataU, type="percent", main="Yes")

In the frequency bar chart above, we observe that those who were drug users and did receive the vaccine, appear to be less effected than those who didnt receive the drug, and those who didnt contract the virus, whether they took the drug or not, showed no significant difference.

Similarly, when we observe the percentage bar chart above, it appears that those drug users who contracted the virus and took the vaccine were less likely to contract the virus than those who didnt take the vaccine. Those who didnt contract the virus showed no apparent difference between those who took the vaccine and those who didnt and were drug users.

DataU=filter(FinalData,DrugUser=="no")
barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataU)

barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=DataU, type="percent", main="no")

In the above frequency bar chart, it appears that those who are not drug users and have contracted the virus, were less likely to get the virus if they took the drug than those who didnt take the drug. Those who didnt contract the virus showed no significant difference whether they took the drug or not.

Similarly it appears that in the above percentage bar chart, that those who had the virus who are not drug users and took the vaccine were less likely to contract the virus than those who didnt take the vaccine. Those who did not have the virus showed no significant difference whether they took the vaccine or not.

According to the xtabs chart above, those who are drug users that were infected by the virus 43.29 percent took the vaccine and 56.71 percent who did not take the vaccine, were infected. Overall, drug users infected were less likely to be infected than those who didnt take the vaccine. However, it appears that there is not a significant difference between those who took the vaccine and those who didnt.

chisq.test(table1)
##

The above Chi-Square Statistic Chart shows an overall P-value of approx. .000000000005 which is below the 0.05 and true odds ratio is not equal to 1 making it impossible to prove a non relation to the targeted sets of data ran above.

Discussion and Conclusion

In conclusion, we reject the null Hypothesis that among the target population in each following data, the vaccine has no effect on whether one contracts the virus or not in favor of the alternative hypothesis that among the target population in each of the following sets of data, the vaccine does have an effect on whether one contracts the virus or not.

It appears that between genders, women were less likely to contract the virus when taking the virus than men.

It appears that gays were more likely to contract the virus than straights when taking the vaccine.

Lastly it appears that drug users were more likely to contract the virus than non-drug users when taking the vaccine.

Overall, we can conclude that among the sub-populations whether taking the vaccine or not taking the vaccine can have a negative or positive effect in relation to their sub-groups such as the above sub-groups between genders, and various lifestyles.
